<BlogPostLayout
  title="Wood Heater Smoking? Here's Why — and How to Fix It"
  description="If your wood heater is smoking into the room, filling the house with smoke, or producing excessive smoke from the flue, here's how to diagnose and fix it."
  publishDate="April 2026"
  readTime="6 min"
>

  <p><strong>A smoking wood heater isn't just unpleasant — it's a health risk.</strong> Smoke in the room means carbon monoxide and fine particles are entering your living space. It won't fix itself. Here's how to diagnose the cause and fix it.</p>

  <h2>Is the Smoke Coming Into the Room or Out the Flue?</h2>

  <p>The answer makes a difference to what's causing it:</p>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.65rem;margin:1.1rem 0 1.6rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;background:#f5f0e8;border-radius:10px;padding:.9rem 1rem;">
      <span style="font-size:1.3rem;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">🏠</span>
      <div><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Smoke coming into the room</strong><br/><span style="font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;">The heater isn't drawing properly. Smoke is escaping through the door or vents instead of going up the flue. Usually a draw or pressure issue.</span></div>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;background:#f5f0e8;border-radius:10px;padding:.9rem 1rem;">
      <span style="font-size:1.3rem;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">🌫️</span>
      <div><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Heavy smoke from the flue outside</strong><br/><span style="font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;">The heater is drawing but burning inefficiently. Usually a wet wood or restricted airflow problem.</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Most people mean the first one — smoke coming back into the room. That's what most of this guide covers.</p>

  <h2>The Most Common Reasons a Wood Heater Smokes Into the Room</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.8rem;margin:1.1rem 0 1.6rem;">

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        1. The flue is cold (cold downdraught)<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">This is the most common cause, especially at the start of the season or on the first fire of the day. When the flue is cold, the air inside is heavier than the warm air in the room — so instead of drawing up, cold air pushes down and forces smoke back in.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Prime the flue before lighting. Roll a sheet of newspaper into a torch, hold it up inside the firebox near the flue opening, and light it. Hold it there for 30–60 seconds until you feel the air start pulling upward. Then light your fire immediately. Keep the air controls fully open for the first 20–30 minutes.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        2. The flue is blocked or partially blocked<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Creosote buildup, a bird's nest, leaves, or a collapsed flue cap can all restrict the flue enough to prevent proper draw. If the flue is heavily blocked, even a well-lit fire will push smoke back into the room because there's nowhere for it to go.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">How to tell:</strong> The problem happens consistently, not just on cold starts. Priming the flue doesn't help. The fire struggles even with all air controls open.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Professional flue clean. This isn't something you can safely diagnose or clear yourself — the blockage is up in the pipe, not in the firebox.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        3. Wet or unseasoned wood<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Wet wood burns at a much lower temperature, produces far more smoke than dry wood, and creates weaker draw through the flue — which means more smoke finds its way back into the room. The fire is also harder to get going and doesn't stay lit well.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">How to tell:</strong> Knock two pieces of wood together. Dry wood makes a sharp crack. Wet wood makes a dull thud. Wet wood also often has visible moisture or feels heavy for its size. The fire will hiss and steam.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Source properly seasoned hardwood — red gum, ironbark or box that has been dried for at least 12 months. Store wood undercover, off the ground, with airflow around it.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        4. Negative air pressure in the house<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Modern well-sealed homes can create negative air pressure — meaning the house is slightly depressurised relative to outside. When this happens, the flue can't draw properly because there's not enough replacement air coming in. Range hoods, exhaust fans and ducted heating systems all exhaust air out of the house and can cause or worsen this.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">How to tell:</strong> Open a window slightly while the heater is running. If the smoking stops immediately, negative pressure is the cause.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Crack a window slightly near the heater when it's running. Turn off exhaust fans while the fire is going. Some homes need an air vent installed near the heater — a tradesperson can advise on this.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        5. Air controls are closed too early<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Closing the air vents too soon after lighting starves the fire of oxygen before it's properly established. A fire that isn't burning hot enough won't generate enough updraft to draw smoke up the flue consistently.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Keep air controls fully open for at least the first 20–30 minutes, until the fire is burning strongly and the firebox is fully up to temperature. Then gradually reduce the air — don't close them completely until there's a solid bed of coals.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        6. The flue is too heavily built up with creosote<span style="font-size:1.1rem;color:#c8500a;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">
        <p style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Even without a full blockage, heavy creosote buildup narrows the internal diameter of the flue. A narrower flue means less draw — and less draw means more smoke backing up into the room. This gets progressively worse over seasons if the flue isn't cleaned annually.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">How to tell:</strong> The heater used to work fine but has gradually gotten worse over one or two seasons. The problem isn't just on cold starts — it's consistent.</p>
        <p style="margin:.75rem 0 0;"><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fix:</strong> Professional flue clean. Once the buildup is removed, draw typically improves significantly.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

  </div>

