  <h2>Quick Diagnosis — Work Through This in Order</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.5rem;margin:1rem 0 1.4rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Is this the first fire of the season or day?</strong> Try priming the flue with a rolled newspaper torch before lighting.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Does opening a window help?</strong> Yes = negative air pressure issue. Crack a window when running the heater.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Is the wood dry?</strong> Knock two pieces together — sharp crack = dry, dull thud = too wet. Try different wood.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Are the air controls fully open?</strong> Keep them open for the first 20–30 minutes minimum.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.4;flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
      <span style="font-size:.97rem;color:#3a3a34;line-height:1.6;"><strong>Still smoking after all of the above?</strong> The flue needs a professional clean — there's likely a blockage or heavy creosote buildup.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background:#fff3cd;border-left:4px solid #c8500a;border-radius:8px;padding:1rem 1.1rem;margin:1.4rem 0;">
    <strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Don't keep using a smoking heater without investigating why.</strong>
    <p style="margin:.4rem 0 0;font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">Smoke entering the room means carbon monoxide is also potentially entering the room. CO is odourless and colourless — you won't necessarily smell it. If your heater is consistently smoking back into the room, treat it as a safety issue and get it checked before the next use.</p>
  </div>

