  <h2>What About Heavy Smoke From the Flue Outside?</h2>

  <p>If the smoke is going up and out the flue but is thick, white or dark grey, that's a combustion efficiency problem rather than a draw problem. The main causes are wet wood (produces thick white steam-smoke), a fire that's running too low (close the air controls less), or a heater that's been slumbering overnight on a very low setting.</p>

  <p>A little visible water vapour from the flue on startup is normal — it clears within a few minutes once the system warms up. Thick ongoing smoke that doesn't clear is wet wood, almost every time.</p>

  <p>Heavy dark smoke at any point can also indicate something has been burned that shouldn't have — treated timber, cardboard, rubbish or plastic. Stick to dry hardwood only.</p>

